address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: daezjn
text: We bought our ticket for Prambanan temple prior at Borobudur as they offered a special deal of two locations for one price at the ticket counter- unfortunately the Borobudur tickets for walking amongst the stones were sold out so this offer to walk only outside the stone area and a entry to Prambanan was the best alternative option. FYI buy your Borobudur tickets online a week in advance- this is a new process implemented two months ago! With the ticket purchased from Borobudur as ‘foreigners’ we enter through a different entrance where it is air conditioned, with fresh clean toilets and we get a free bottle of water. There is also the option to hire a professional guide (110k). Personally, I found this temple more enjoyable than Borobudur. We had free range to explore the grounds without the limitations instilled at Borobudur at a flat rate price. There are actually four temple spots to visit. I highly recommend checking out the smaller ones first as they aren’t far from the main one and are hardly visited but are just as fascinating and beautiful- they are also older than the main site. There are options to cycle or take a large golf cart there but it’s unnecessary as they aren’t that far. However, the walk to the exit is a very long way and ends with a long journey through souvenir shops, drink stands, etc. with crowds of visitors heading the same way. Prambanan temple is totally worth visiting, friendlier staff and better managed compared to Borobudur :) All up we spent about two hours here. If you have extra time, there is also a museum to check out on the way to the exit.
title: Prambanan Temple

text:
Prambanan is an incredible historical site!!!
The temple complex, a UNESCO World Heritage site, is stunning with its tall Hindu temples and intricate stone carvings.
It’s a peaceful and spacious place to explore, offering a glimpse into Indonesia’s rich cultural and religious history.
I enjoyed learning about the stories behind the temples, particularly the mythological tales depicted in the carvings.
The site is well-maintained, and you’ll find plenty of opportunities for photos.
It can get quite hot, so be sure to stay hydrated and wear sun protection.
Overall, Prambanan is a must-see attraction for anyone visiting Yogyakarta, especially if you’re interested in history, culture, or architecture.

I really enjoyed this temple.   For me the highlight was less the main Prambanan Temple but Sewu Temple.   It doesn't appear that most people get there as it's probably a 1.5km walk down a paved road (or you can rent a bicycle or get a ride on a golf cart).

Sewu Temple was quiet and gave me a better feeling of what the complex might have been like without hordes of tourists.  In fact, I was only 1 of probably 4 people that were at that temple versus thousands of people at the main Prambanan Temple.

The grounds are lovely and it felt less "stage managed" than Brobordor.

name: Shaheen Shahmirzadi
text:
In a land where myths and legends whisper through the ages, where the earth itself seems to hum with the echoes of ancient gods, stands the magnificent Prambanan Temple—a citadel of stone that reaches toward the heavens.

My wife and I ventured to this sacred site, drawn by tales of its grandeur, and what we found surpassed even our wildest imaginings. The temple complex unfolded before us like a grand tapestry, each towering spire a testament to the power and beauty of a forgotten era.

As we wandered through the hallowed grounds, the air seemed to thrum with ancient magic. The temples rose around us, their intricately carved walls telling stories of gods and heroes long past. We could almost hear the clang of celestial battles, the murmur of divine councils, as we walked among the statues that have stood watch for centuries.

The central temple loomed above all, a mighty fortress of stone dedicated to the trinity of Hindu gods. Its spires pierced the sky, each one more impressive than the last, their shadows dancing in the golden light of the setting sun. We felt as if we had been transported to a realm where the gods themselves had walked, where every stone held the weight of history and divinity.

In the quiet corners of the complex, we found moments of serene reflection. The gardens, lush and vibrant, seemed to cradle the temples in a protective embrace, while the surrounding statues stood as silent guardians of the past. It was here, in the stillness of these sacred grounds, that we felt a deep connection to the souls who had come before us, pilgrims and kings alike, drawn to this place by its overwhelming power.

Prambanan is not just a temple; it is a portal to another world, a place where the boundary between the mortal and the divine blurs, where history and myth are woven together in stone. My wife and I left Prambanan with our hearts full, awed by the majesty of what we had seen and the stories that had come alive in our imaginations.

For those who seek adventure, wonder, and a touch of the divine, Prambanan Temple is a destination like no other. It is a journey into the heart of ancient majesty, a place where the past is ever-present, and where the gods still linger, waiting to share their stories with those who are willing to listen.
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia
name: cinty ionescu
text:
It's an impressive place to visit especially that it is still a temple in use, therefore the 9th floor isn't open to the public. It is one of the most magnificent Buddhist monuments in the world and a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Constructed in the 9th century, this colossal structure is renowned for its intricate design and profound spiritual significance.

The temple is built in the form of a giant stupa and consists of nine stacked platforms, six square and three circular, topped by a central dome. As visitors ascend through the levels, they encounter a series of beautifully carved relief panels that depict the life of the Buddha and the teachings of Buddhism. There are over 2,600 relief panels, each telling a story that guides pilgrims on their spiritual journey.

The architectural brilliance of Borobudur is complemented by its stunning surroundings, with the lush green hills and distant volcanic mountains providing a breathtaking backdrop. The view from the top is nothing short of magical.

It is inconvenient that you don't have the time to explore it in depth as the guide of each group entering the temple is rushing people around. While the information provided by the guide was interesting and helpful for understanding the temple, it's a pitty that one cannot explore the impressive amount of stone carvings and the Buddhist tales included in them. The temple is truly beautiful and the atmosphere at sunset was magic. It's worth noting that everything is greatly kept, including the green areas. I just wish the management wouldn't force upon visitors such a short amount of time within the temple's walls. I hope to be back one day.

To avoid waking up around midnight for the long journey from the city to here to catch the sunrise, you can consider booking a night stay at the hotel/resort that is just at the foot of this complex.  The hotel/resort has decent rooms, serves meals and has a small showroom playing some videos of the temple complex.

If you do stay here, you will get to wake up at around 4-5 am and take a nice stroll to the temple complex, leisurely climb up and find a good spot to wait for the sunrise.

The entire complex is so serene and peaceful.  As the sky brightens up, the beauty of the temple slowly unfold.  Spend time to absorb all the views, stupas and wall engravings.

Another item on my bucket list checked ✅

The parking is far from the temple entrance and you have to walk quite a bit. Then catch a shuttle bus. Bring plenty of water and an umbrella to protect yourselves from the sun.

We purchased our tickets in advance to make sure to climb the temple structure and not only see it from the ground.

You get a pair of sandals, a tour guide and a bottle of water. You have only one hour on the temple structure. The best part for us was the top level, so don't spend too long on the lower levels.

name: Genta
text:
Borobudur Temple is an incredible experience! I took the chance to go up to the actual temple, and it was worth every bit. For locals, tickets are IDR 50K (approx. SGD 4.50 | USD 3.20 | CNY 23 | JPY 470) for the base and IDR 120K (approx. SGD 10.80 | USD 7.70 | CNY 55 | JPY 1,120) to visit the top, with a max of 150 people per session. I chose the 10:30 AM session—probably not the best timing as it’s the hottest part of the day, but still totally worth it!

You get special sandals (included with the ticket) to wear up there, and umbrellas are available to rent for just IDR 10K (approx. SGD 0.90 | USD 0.64 | CNY 4.60 | JPY 93). Such a nice touch! It was my first time visiting the temple, and it did not disappoint. OH, and the ticket also includes a GUIDE! Super helpful, no extra charges, and they explain everything beautifully.

The walk up is a bit hilly and far, so plan your timing wisely. But overall, an unforgettable experience—highly recommended!

text:
Arrived at the counter we’ve been told the bottom part is open only, which is fine since we can see everything from the bottom. We double check twice, “Can we see everything from the bottom?”. Yes. Twice. (Spoiler alert: you can’t see anything from the bottom, no Buddha, no view, no lotus flowers)
We were deceived when we get to the temple, walk around in 10 minutes and that’s it.

When we go back to the ticket counter, they tell us that Monday are cleaning days and that’s why the top part is closed. Understandable, but we still paid $50 to not see anything. This is not what we’ve been told when we bought the ticket.

They did not believe anything we told them. They said we stayed 2 hours in the temple, which we disagreed to and had to prove to them by the ticket the time that we got there.

Basically lied to us on the experience we would have and offered to go to the museum on the way back. Museum is closed as well.

Overall I wish things were clearer and we could have been helped by the staff for the price that we paid. Beautiful temple regardless, but from what you see in the pictures online, this is not what we received.

A Journey to the Majestic Borobudur Temple

Recently, I had the privilege of visiting the Borobudur Temple, an iconic UNESCO World Heritage Site in the Jogjakarta region of Indonesia. Words fall short in capturing the sheer magnificence of this historical wonder. The temple’s beauty, vastness, and intricate architecture left me absolutely overwhelmed.

The Borobudur Temple stands as a testament to ancient engineering and spiritual dedication. Its massive structure, adorned with detailed carvings and over 2,600 relief panels, tells timeless stories of Buddhist teachings and cultural history. Walking through its nine stacked platforms, I was amazed by the precision and artistry of a structure built in the 8th and 9th centuries, long before modern technology existed. The panoramic views of the surrounding lush landscapes from the top made the experience even more surreal.

Our journey was enriched by the guidance of Sylvi, an exceptional tour guide with an impressive depth of knowledge about the history and ancient engineering of the temple. Her engaging storytelling and ability to connect the past with the present added immense value to our visit. Sylvi’s passion and expertise truly brought the temple to life, allowing us to appreciate its historical and spiritual significance on a deeper level.

Visiting the Borobudur Temple was an unforgettable experience—both humbling and inspiring. I highly recommend it to anyone with a love for history, architecture, and cultural exploration. And if you get the chance, do tour with Sylvi; she’s a gem who elevates the experience to a whole new level.

text:
Borobudur is one of the most famous Buddhist sites in Indonesia and one of the greatest architectural wonders of Buddhism worldwide. Its grand and awe-inspiring design, combined with unparalleled artistic expression, leaves visitors in awe. As a massive Buddhist temple, Borobudur features a complex and profound architectural layout that symbolizes the Buddhist cosmology.

First, the scale and architectural design of Borobudur are striking. Built with over two million volcanic stones, the structure has nine levels, each representing different stages of enlightenment in Buddhism. The circular stupa at the top symbolizes the ultimate realm of Nirvana, evoking a sense of serenity and transcendence.

Secondly, the relief art of Borobudur is unparalleled, with thousands of reliefs carved into its walls that depict Buddhist stories. These carvings not only convey the essence of Buddhist teachings but also reflect the social life, culture, and natural landscapes of ancient Java. The intricate craftsmanship of these carvings showcases the exceptional skills of ancient artisans and allows modern visitors to experience the spiritual and philosophical world of that era.

Lastly, Borobudur holds deep religious significance as a pilgrimage site. It is not only a place of spiritual practice for Buddhists but also a sacred destination for people around the world seeking spiritual cleansing. Standing before this thousand-year-old temple, one can feel the profound history, the endless power of faith, and the eternal pursuit of spiritual enlightenment.

Borobudur, with its magnificent architecture, exquisite artistry, and deep religious significance, is a gem in the heritage of human culture, forever radiating the light of wisdom and faith.

Borobudur Temple is nothing short of a masterpiece, a testament to the grandeur and ingenuity of ancient civilizations. As one of the largest and most impressive Buddhist monuments in the world, it offers an awe-inspiring experience that is sure to leave a lasting impression on anyone fortunate enough to visit.

From the moment you approach Borobudur, the sheer scale and intricacy of the structure take your breath away. Each level of the temple reveals a new layer of stunning detail – from the intricately carved stone reliefs that tell stories of ancient wisdom to the towering stupas that stand as silent sentinels against the backdrop of lush green hills. The craftsmanship and artistry that went into creating this monument are truly remarkable.

As you ascend the terraces, you not only feel a sense of physical elevation but also a spiritual one. The journey to the top is symbolic, representing a path to enlightenment, and the panoramic views that greet you at the summit are nothing short of spectacular. Standing at the peak, surrounded by mist-covered mountains and the lush landscape of Central Java, you can’t help but feel a profound connection to the past and a deep appreciation for the cultural heritage that Borobudur represents.

Visiting Borobudur is more than just a sightseeing trip; it’s an immersive experience that takes you on a journey through time, culture, and spirituality. Whether you’re a history buff, a cultural enthusiast, or simply someone who appreciates the beauty of human achievement, Borobudur Temple is a must-visit destination that will leave you in awe of its grandeur.

In summary, Borobudur Temple is a majestic and unforgettable destination. Its stunning architecture, rich history, and spiritual significance make it one of the most extraordinary places on Earth. A visit here is not just recommended – it’s essential for anyone exploring Indonesia.

name: Ameeruddin Javid Bashha
text:
Borobudur Temple, an iconic UNESCO World Heritage Site in Indonesia, is a masterpiece of ancient Buddhist architecture and intricate stone carvings.

Renowned as the largest Buddhist temple ever built, it represents the essence of Buddhist art and teachings. Visitors are captivated by the panoramic views of the surrounding landscapes from the top and the serene atmosphere that invites reflection and peace of mind. Exploring the temple offers a profound connection to history and Buddhist culture, making it a must-visit for enthusiasts of history, art and spirituality.

The temple is maintained well and managed efficiently, providing a comfortable experience for visitors. Guided tours, often led by knowledgeable English-speaking guides, enrich the visit with detailed insights into the temple's history and architecture.

In order to fully appreciate the site, many recommend booking tickets in advance due to the limited daily capacity. The experience includes a pair of sandals, a bottle of water, and one hour on the temple structure, with the top level being a highlight. Sunrise visits are particularly breathtaking, as golden rays illuminate the temple and create a timeless, magical atmosphere.

However, visitors should be prepared for logistical challenges. Parking is far from the temple entrance, requiring a lengthy walk followed by a shuttle bus ride. It's advisable to bring water and an umbrella to manage the heat and sun. Despite these minor inconveniences, Borobudur Temple remains an enlightening experience.

Some visitors find the entry process and site navigation to be confusing and were disappointed with mandatory group tours, which limited their freedom to explore. Others criticized the high ticket prices and limited access to the temple's upper levels on specific days, particularly Mondays, when cleaning is scheduled. Complaints of unclear communication from staff regarding restricted access and ticket policies also surfaced.

On one occasion, visitors felt deceived after being assured they could view the temple’s highlights from the lower levels, only to find limited visibility of key features like Buddha statues and lotus flowers.

Despite these challenges, Borobudur Temple’s beauty, historical significance, and the enriching experience it offers make it a highly recommended destination for those visiting Indonesia.

Built in the 9th century during the reign of the Sailendra Dynasty, Borobudur stands as a monumental masterpiece of ancient architecture and spiritual devotion. The temple is designed as a massive step pyramid, consisting of nine stacked platforms: six square and three circular, topped by a central dome. It features over 2,600 relief panels and 504 Buddha statues, making it one of the most intricately decorated temples in the world.

text:
**Review of Prambanan Temple: A Marvel of Ancient Hindu Architecture in Indonesia**

Prambanan Temple, a UNESCO World Heritage Site located in Central Java, Indonesia, stands as a stunning testament to the architectural prowess of ancient Hindu civilization. Built in the 9th century, this temple complex is not only an emblem of spiritual devotion but also a masterpiece of design and craftsmanship.

The intricate details of the stone carvings are simply breathtaking. Each relief tells a story from Hindu epics like the Ramayana and Mahabharata, showcasing the artists' skill and dedication. The towering spires of the temple, particularly the main shrine dedicated to Shiva, reach majestically towards the sky, symbolizing a connection between the earthly and the divine.

The layout of Prambanan is meticulously planned, reflecting the harmonious relationship between architecture and nature. The symmetrical design and the strategic placement of the temples create a sense of balance and tranquility that enhances the spiritual experience for visitors.

Walking through the temple grounds, one can’t help but appreciate the engineering marvels of the time, including the use of local volcanic stone, which not only provided durability but also added a unique aesthetic quality to the structures.

Overall, Prambanan Temple is a remarkable representation of Indonesia's rich cultural heritage, offering insight into the artistic and architectural achievements of the Hindu kingdom. It is a must-visit for anyone interested in history, architecture, or spirituality, leaving a lasting impression of Indonesia's ancient glory.

name: M. Maietta
text:
Prambanan Temple, a 9th-century architectural marvel in Central Java, Indonesia, stands as the largest Hindu temple complex in the country. Dedicated to the Trimurti—Brahma the Creator, Vishnu the Preserver, and Shiva the Destroyer—this UNESCO World Heritage Site captivates visitors with its towering spires and intricate stone carvings.

Legend weaves through Prambanan’s stones, telling the tale of Princess Rara Jonggrang. According to local folklore, Prince Bandung Bondowoso sought her hand in marriage, but she set a seemingly impossible condition: he must build a thousand temples in a single night. With the help of supernatural beings, the prince completed 999 temples. However, the princess deceived him by causing the villagers to create the illusion of dawn, preventing the final temple’s completion. In his wrath, the prince cursed Rara Jonggrang, turning her into stone—a statue that now resides in the temple complex.  ￼

The temple’s walls narrate the epic Ramayana through detailed bas-reliefs, bringing ancient stories to life. The central Shiva temple soars 47 meters high, surrounded by temples honoring Brahma and Vishnu, each adorned with statues and carvings that showcase the artistry of the era.  ￼

Despite suffering damage from earthquakes and volcanic eruptions over the centuries, Prambanan has undergone extensive restoration, allowing it to reclaim its former splendor. Today, it not only serves as a testament to Indonesia’s rich cultural heritage but also as a vibrant center for cultural performances, such as the Ramayana Ballet, which is regularly performed at the temple complex.  ￼

A visit to Prambanan offers an enchanting journey through history, legend, and art—a must-see for anyone exploring Indonesia.
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Shuja Khan
text: A 9th century temple, the largest in Indonesia and the second larger in South East Asia. It originally consisted 240 temples in different sizes but over the course of life a lot of them were reduced to debris by earth quakes etc, the major earth quake doing the most damage in 16th century. Reconstruction work of the temples started in 1930 and ceased due to economic conditions in 1940s due to world war ll. The bigger main temple shiva was restored in 1953 and inaugurated by the first president Sukarno. The Brahma temple was reconstructed in 1987 and the Vishnu temple was restored in 1991. It was added to UNESCO world heritage site in 1991. There are other 3 temples located on the site which is included in the entry ticket. The other 3 temples that are located within the complex are Lumbung Bubrah and Sewu. You can rent a bicycle or walk or take a van to these temples.

name: Cazzal
text:
Prambanan Temple is a stunning Hindu temple complex located in Central Java, Indonesia. It is renowned for its tall, pointed architecture and intricate carvings. The temple was built in the 9th century and is dedicated to the Trimurti, which represents the three main gods of Hinduism: Brahma the creator, Vishnu the preserver, and Shiva the destroyer.

The complex consists of several temples, with the main ones being the three large temples dedicated to these deities. Prambanan is not only a UNESCO World Heritage Site but also one of the largest Hindu temple complexes in Southeast Asia. The temple's design is characterized by its towering spires and detailed reliefs that depict stories from Hindu epics such as the Ramayana.

Visitors to Prambanan can explore the beautiful gardens surrounding the temples, enjoy traditional performances, and learn about the rich history and culture of the region. The site is an important symbol of Indonesia's cultural heritage and continues to attract tourists from around the world..
title: Prambanan Temple

text:
Caṇḍi Prambanan is the largest Hindu temple building in Indonesia which was built in the 8th - 9th century AD

Prambanan Temple Compounds consist of Prambanan Temple (also called Loro Jonggrang), Sewu Temple, Bubrah Temple and Lumbung Temple. Prambanan Temple it self is a complex consisting of 240 temples. All the mentioned temples form the Prambanan Archaeological Park and were built during the heyday of Sailendra’s powerful dynasty in Java in the 8th century AD. These compounds are located on the border between the two provinces of Yogyakarta and Central Java on Java Island.
title: Prambanan Temple

text:
Discover the splendor of Prambanan, an awe-inspiring 9th-century Hindu temple complex near Yogyakarta, Indonesia. This UNESCO World Heritage site boasts intricate architecture and stunning stone carvings dedicated to the Hindu trinity of Brahma, Vishnu, and Shiva.

Stroll through the lush gardens and explore the main temple and its surrounding shrines, each telling a story of rich cultural heritage and devotion. Don't miss the evening Ramayana ballet performance, which brings ancient legends to life against the backdrop of these magnificent temples.

Perfect for history buffs, culture enthusiasts, and travelers seeking a glimpse into Indonesia's glorious past. Plan your visit and immerse yourself in the timeless beauty of Prambanan!

name: daezjn
text: The famous temple is more than we anticipated! Buy your Borobudur tickets online a week in advance- this is a new process implemented two months ago! Unfortunately, the Borobudur tickets for walking amongst the stones for a higher price were sold out (disappointing as we had flown over just to see it and had driven 2 hours from town) but the second best option is the ticket offer to walk only outside the stone area and an entry to Prambanan temple was the best alternative as we were heading to Prambana after. Our ticket for Prambanan temple and Borobudur temple is a special deal of two locations for one price at the Borobudur ticket counter. Borobudur is beautiful and quite an awe-inspiring structure to see. As a Buddhist it felt like a pilgrimage for myself. However, do also visit the bodhi tree nearby to meditate and pay respects 🙏 monks do come visit here at 10am. Highly recommend coming early for less crowds as it gets very busy! The new architecture surrounding the main entrance, staff and setup right now seems haphazard and disorganized. I found some counter ticket staff rude while others very helpful. The public toilet was filthy but the eatery area was nice and clean. Hopefully the experience here will get better over time. Personally I found my experience at Prambanan temple was more pleasant :)

We didn't book in advanced so couldn't go up onto the temple. Reading some other reviews about just getting the grounds ticket, we almost didn't go. That would however have been a big mistake. Only 1500 people can go up per day, but 1000s more visit the grounds every day, so don't feel like you are missing out if you aren't one of the select few who got a spot to go up. Seeing the temple from 'the grounds' meaning you can walk around it is also impressive. You still get to see the impressive size of the structure the thousands of reliefs and hundreds of Buddha statues, etc. Definitely still worth a visit even if you don't get an 'upstairs ticket'.

Also the souvenir 'maze' is not that bad. Just walk through if you don't want to buy. We bought some souvenirs at good prices, just go the the stalls at the very end for the best prices.

text:
We went to Borobodur on a Saturday just before 3:30PM.
Fair warning: while the temple closes only at 4:30PM, the last people to go on the temple leave at 3:30.

We just missed that window so the only thing we could do was just having a stroll around the temple and nothing more.

It is a really nice and detailed temple nonetheless, but the experience was kinda barebones. The rest of the things on the grounds were under construction so except for the temple there wasn't a whole lot to do.

I'm not a Karen so I'm not redacting stars for not being able to go up since I should have done my research but I am redacting a star for the going-home-experience.

The only way to get out is through a series of small stalls in a very narrow alleyway with people trying to sell you things.
The "series" of stalls is more like a series that runs for 23 seasons. It's REALLY long and it bothered us. You'll be shuffling behind people who are slower than you whom you can't pass and you can't even look at nice scenery, just endless stalls.

name: Jelly Tree
text: The largest Buddhist temple in Indonesia and one of its iconic sights. I was lucky to visit this in 2014 when you could walk around freely each floor of the temple. Most people rush to the top but I really recommend that you enjoy each floor of the temple before you reach the top. The stone carvings are beautiful and show how humans according to the Buddhist belief gradually become enlightened with the teachings of Buddha. The higher to the top you get, the more enlightened the humans appear in the stone carvings. There are a lot of Buddha statues and unfortunately some without heads. These have been stolen by thiefs and sold around the world. When you leave Borobudur, you have to pass through a lot of vendors, which wasn't very pleasant. But the temple and the stone carvings are incredible.

text:
Borobudur Temple is a breathtaking masterpiece and an absolute must-visit for anyone traveling to Indonesia. The largest Buddhist temple in the world, it’s a marvel of ancient architecture and spiritual significance. The intricate carvings and the sheer scale of the temple complex are awe-inspiring.

I recommend arriving early in the morning to catch the sunrise, which casts a magical glow over the stupas and surrounding landscape. The views are simply stunning and provide an unforgettable experience. The site is well-maintained, with clear pathways and informative signage that enhances the visit.

Guided tours are available and highly recommended to fully appreciate the historical and cultural context of the temple. The local guides are knowledgeable and passionate, adding depth to the visit.

Overall, Borobudur Temple is a gem of Indonesia and a highlight of Southeast Asia. Don't miss the chance to explore this incredible historical site!
title: Borobudur Temple

name: Kenneth Cheng
text:
One of the best organised ancient temple sites I have visited. The limit on visitors and scheduling meant that everyone got a fair share of experiencing and immersing in the beauty of this site.
Be aware that you need some level of fitness and mobility to ascend and descend the ancient steps. Also, the sun and heat can affect some people more than others.
Unfortunately, it also created a speculative temple ascend ticket situation, with local tour operators and guides buying in bulk during the peak season. Which meant that some guides have to buy tickets at inflated prices if you were a 'last minute' visitor (ie you booked your day tour the day before).
Also, they do force you to walk through a long trek of market stalls prior to existing the protected area. It seems this was a means to organise the many market stalls that use to inhabit the surrounds into something more controllable.

name: ILoveBippus
text:
Lovely temple complex in Central Java.  Easy to get to by bus from Yogyakarta.  Went in January and it is very very hot.  Make sure to bring a hat, sunscreen and water.  The foreigner tickets are less than $400k and you get a bottle of water. Yes it’s pricey for Indonesia but I don’t mind since the funds go for all the needed restoration work.   Also hired a guide for 120k because I have no idea about any Hindu history.

You can buy a combo ticket for Borobudur here. You get a discount for getting the tickets for both places.  You can only get the discounted tickets at Prambanan.  I went the opposite route and went to Borobudur first and didn’t realize they had a special.  Both places are worth the visit.
It takes 3 years to restore one small temple, so it will take them about 600 years to finish it up.  There are hundreds of smaller temples. The large ones are amazing. The detail of the carvings is crazy.

I happened to be almost as popular as the temples with the kids. Didn’t bother me. I don’t mind making them happy with pictures.

The complex grounds also contain 3 more temple areas that are Buddhist.  Walked over to them and only saw a few other people.  It was nice to get away from the crowds, though it wasn’t crowded, and have some alone time at these special spiritual places.

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia
name: Md Shanto Rahman
text:
Borobudur Temple, a UNESCO World Heritage Site in Indonesia, is a breathtaking masterpiece of ancient architecture and culture. Built in the 9th century, this massive Buddhist temple is an awe-inspiring combination of intricate carvings, grand stupas, and stunning views. The temple's design represents the Buddhist concept of the universe, with its three levels symbolizing desire, form, and formlessness.

The carvings on the walls are incredibly detailed, depicting stories from Buddhist scriptures and offering insights into life during that era. The sunrise view from the top of the temple is simply magical and worth the early morning trek.

The surrounding lush greenery and Mount Merapi in the background add to its serene ambiance. The site is well-maintained, but it can get crowded during peak hours. Hiring a guide or using an audio guide enhances the experience by explaining the temple's history and symbolism.

However, visitors should be mindful of the rules, such as dressing modestly and respecting the sacred space. Accessibility for people with mobility issues can be a challenge due to the steep stairs.

Overall, Borobudur Temple is a must-visit for history enthusiasts, spiritual seekers, and travelers alike. It offers a unique blend of history, culture, and spirituality that leaves a lasting impression.
title: Borobudur Temple

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia

- The temple itself is very impressive! Staffs here are supper friendly, helpful and supportive. However, my impression about this place was not really good and i did not really enjoy. So, overall I just rate 3 stars.
- I did not search much infomation before my visit, so a little bit confused at first :)). Things i dont like: 1, very very crowded. 2, foreigners must scan QR code to buy ticket in the system by themselves, even you are alr there, they dont support buy ticket at the counter. Very inconvenient! 3, the ticket price is such expensive and again, foreigners always pay much more than local people. 4, you must go with a tour guide and a group when going up to the temple and just have an hour, so not really felt free. 5, finally, you have to pass through many vendors and shops to go out even you dont like shopping and no choice.
- My advise: 1, abt transportation, you can take a minivan (20k rp) in front of Bank Indonesia to get to Borobudur bus terminal and walk abt 2km to get to the temple. 2, very important: you should buy ticket in advance and buy 'temple structure ticket' (445k rp), if you want to go up to the temple, because tickets are sold out quickly. I arrived at 11 am and did not buy ticket in advance, just a few tickets left at last sessions 2.30 and 3.30 pm. And just 30 mins later, all tickets were sold out. Though i had to wait but i was still lucky. 3, if your credit card has issue in payment step, you can choose a convenient store nearby and pay there. 4, they will give you flip-flops and you must change shoes before going up to the temple. 5, For 'temple ground ticket' (400k rp), you can buy at the ticket counter and don't need to wait, don't need a tour guide and you can go by yourself, but for this kind of ticket, they just allow you to walk around the yard, not allow to go up to the temple. That's why i advise you to buy ticket in advance and buy 'temple structure ticket' (455k rp).

title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Meigan Swanson
text:
Mesmerizing, magical, incredible to experience. Such a massive complex! We spent 10 hours here (much more than most, I would recommend minimum 2-3 hours).
Please dress modestly (cover shoulders and knees). In Prambanan, most of the original statues are intact! Absolutely amazing. The other temples (Candi Sewu, Lumbung and Bubra) are much less visited and you can explore almost to yourself.

There is a wonderful drinking chocolate shop on the grounds and many creative activities for kids and adults alike (such as painting, games, segway rides, bicycles). Note: you can only rent bikes for 20 minutes (so not enough time to bike to Sewu and also explore it).

When we were there, the restaurant was closed for a reservation. Luckily, you can exit the grounds to eat outside (many many very cheap food shops) and come back in (so keep your ticket!!). The whole space felt very welcoming, professional, and pleasant.
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia

text:
The best place to visit in Yogyakarta

One of my wishlist to visit Prambanan Temple. This place so gorgeous .. luxurious ..
Even though the weather is very hot, I am very happy to be able to visit this place (thanks God for the opportunity🥹)

For domestic tourist, you can buy the ticket via online (it’s only 50k).
Don't forget to bring an umbrella and use sunscreen ☀️

You can also ask the tour guide to explain the history (and be your photographer)
title: Prambanan Temple

It's sad that it's only open until 4 p.m. but it is alright. The parking lot can fit many vehicles and there are also places where you could buy souvenirs. I'll surely cherish my visit to Prambanan. 🗺️🧳

And one more thing!
There's also other activities to do in Prambanan that I didn't visit. Hope you find this review helpful. 🤗
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Qoriyana Nurselvi
text:
Experience the next level of architectural marvel at this temple. Upon arrival, we were greeted with the option of touring the site via a buggy or golf car, ensuring a comfortable and enjoyable ride while exploring. It's essential to apply sunblock and carry an umbrella to shield yourself from the intense sun overhead. Additionally, don't miss the opportunity to visit the deer enclosure and bird sanctuary within the vicinity.

I highly recommend opting for the buggy car tour, priced at IDR 20K per person. The knowledgeable guides provide an insightful tour of the entire site, ensuring you don't miss any highlights. During my visit, I also made a stop at Candi Sewu, which was definitely worth exploring further.
title: Prambanan Temple

It was well managed, starting from parking space, ticketing, toilets, restaurants as well as souvenirs shops.

I have never been so proud of going to a local tourism destination with international standard.

The guide who accompany us was so informative, great sense of humour and a great photographer as well.

Although we are locals, his explanation on the history of the Prambanan Temple was full in English. A good spoken one as well.

During our visit, there's also a music performance, but it's a pitty that there are no available ticket left.

It would be great, going to a concert there with great lighting of the temple.

One of the places of worship for Hindu friends and also a cultural heritage site in Indonesia. To enter is charged IDR 50,000 and inside there are also other services such as tour guide services, bicycle rental, etc. From my point of view, this place is still relatively sustainable, seen from the carvings on the walls of the temple which are still good. There is periodic temple restoration.

Tourists can enter the temple with a certain capacity. If you are lucky, you can directly witness religious ceremonies in that place.

Actually, the place is a complex that comprises 4 temples (Prambanan itself and also Bubrah and Sewu you can see on the photos) and a beautiful park around them. Obviously, the temples couldn't be standing from the 9th century, so these were actually built again. But still, there are many original blocks on any level. Strongly recommended to visit, and it is absolutely worth its 25$.

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Ve Danamaya
text:
Such a stunning place that’s steeped in history. Aside from the intriguing history of Candi Prambanan, its beautiful Hindu architecture draws me in. The wall reliefs which depicts the story of Rama (from the Sanskrit story Ramayana) is very interesting.

If you want to visit Candi Prambanan, make sure to use a lot of sunscreen, wear hats/caps, and bring umbrellas or a fan with you. It is usually very hot in the area. Aside from that, make sure that you are able to climb a bunch of stairs as reaching the main temples (candi) requires them.
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Bella Carina Putri
text:
Prambanan is the biggest Hinduism temple in Java consisting of several buildings. There are also several other small temples in the vicinity which are already influenced by Buddhism, you can see the difference between them on how they carved the symbols in each temple's building. You can visit around 4-5 more temples by 1-2 km walking or taking the tour car there. You also can hire a guide with the English language in the ticketing area if you want to know more about the history of each temple. Though we didn't hire one when we came there, because we prefer to enjoy and explore the environment by ourselves 😊

It's a good place and it's quite crowded when we visit, but there's still room to improve for this tourist spot, so it can be more comfortable to visit, and manageable in each main temple's of Prambanan.
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia

title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia
name: Pitori S
text:
We bought 10:30 timeslot for going up the temple structure. Booked a car via Klook to take us there. We nearly missed our time-slot even though we left the city at 9am.
Our driver took us to the ticket counter and to exchange entry wristbands, we do need to take a queueing number event though we pre-purchased tickets online, there should have a dedicated lane for pre-purchased tickets.
The tour guide — which is included in the price — was great in explaining the history and stories behind the relics. The top view at level 8-9 was beautiful. We had free time here for half an hour.
The museum was closed due to maintenance which a bit disappointing. There are free shuttle ride (the long double carriage ones) and paid ride for vip (single carriage). We spent about 2 hours there in total.
title: Borobudur Temple

One ticket, costing 50k (adult) for locals or KITAP holders, and 25k for kids, grants access to the ground/yard. The other ticket is for going up to the temple. Renting an umbrella costs 5k. Riding a golf car costs 20k per person, and a horse carriage ride (andong) costs 100k per carriage.
title: Borobudur Temple

title: Borobudur Temple

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia
name: SRJ
text:
This UNESCO world heritage site is stupendous, and so beautiful and serene when you reach the top.

However, even when we booked our tickets in advance, the wait to get into the temple took more than an hour as only guided tours are available. Apparently sunrise tours were available pre Covid but this isn’t an option anymore. This was frustrating as it’s really warm and humid (we got one of the earlier slots at 9am).

The array of souvenir shops everyone is forced to walk past as they exit the temple is also torturous.

Our tour guide wasn’t very engaging, but he really did his best and gave the group time to explore the temple.

The view at the top is well earned and really magnificent. You can see Yogyakarta stretched across you and the stupas are just beautiful. Of course, despite all the small annoyances - Borobudur is worth the visit.
title: Borobudur Temple

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia
name: L T
text: I enjoyed the experience. The visit and tour of the temple was orderly and well organised. But a ticket based on either local or foreigner rate and you’ll then enter to exchange your shoes for a pair of straw slippers to put on during the entire visit. You’ll be given a bag to store and carry your shoes with you. You’’ll also be given a small bottle of mineral water. The visitors are divided into smaller groups of 10-15 to be taken on a tour by a guide that speaks your language. You will be given a card with your group number. Go to the waiting hall and wait for your group number to be announced to start the tour. Our tour was 3 pm. Be warned - carry a fan, wear a hat, tie up long hair, bring water (the small complimentary bottle is not enough), wear sunscreen. IT WAS HOT AND THE CLIMB IS STEEP. So, if you have knee or mobility issues, this will be a challenge. But the getting to the top makes it worth it with spectacular views. The way out is a long maze of getting through souvenir stalls. I feel sorry for the stall holders as it was so hot. If you can, do stop and buy something, to make their time worthwhile.
title: Borobudur Temple

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia
name: ILoveBippus
text:
Loved this place.  Foreigners have to pay a lot more than locals. But they use the extra money for restoration and maintenance.  They only allow 150 per hour into the temple and you have to have a guide.  Got a ticket and only had to wait about 30-45 minutes for the next tour group.  They give you special sandals to protect the temple and then you get them as a souvenir. We had an amazing guide that is very knowledgeable about the temple and it history.

The tour lasted about 40 minutes and we still had 20 minutes left for our tour. So we were able to walk around, relax and check out the temple at our own pace.

Took an overpriced shuttle from Yogyakarta then shared a taxi coming back.
title: Borobudur Temple

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia
name: Fadhil Amadan
text:
The Borobudur Temple, a UNESCO World Heritage site, is undeniably a must-visit destination that seamlessly blends history, spirituality, and architectural grandeur.

Stepping into this ancient monument is like taking a journey back in time, surrounded by the intricate carvings and majestic stupas that tell the tales of a bygone era. The serene ambiance, especially during sunrise or sunset, adds a mystical touch to the experience, making it a pilgrimage for both locals and tourists alike.

While the historical and spiritual significance of Borobudur is awe-inspiring, I couldn’t help but notice a few areas that could enhance the overall visitor experience. The vast green expanse surrounding the temple, while charming, could benefit from a bit of grooming. A well-maintained lawn would not only add to the aesthetic appeal but also provide a comfortable spot for visitors to relax and soak in the atmosphere.

Additionally, the introduction of more public seating areas could be a thoughtful improvement. Considering the number of visitors exploring the temple grounds, having strategically placed benches would offer a welcomed respite for tired feet and an opportunity to contemplate the marvels of Borobudur.

In conclusion, Borobudur Temple is a cultural gem that has withstood the test of time. Its grandeur and historical significance are undeniable. With a few enhancements to the surrounding greenery and the addition of more seating areas, the experience for visitors could be even more delightful. This is a place where the past meets the present, and with a little care, it could continue to be a timeless destination for generations to come.
title: Borobudur Temple

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia

text:
The largest compound Buddhist temple in the world has been listed as UNESCO World Heritage since 1991. The 9th-century Mahayana temple consists of hundreds of Buddha statues and intricate reliefs that was built magically by human in a symmetric architecture. The panoramic view from the top will leave you in awe!

Unfortunately, most of the broken structures were kept in the museum as the temple was heavily covered deep in the forest when its first discovered

Including 432 seated statues and 72 further images that has been restored with the UNESCO’s help in the 1970s. You can notice that some of Buddha statues are headless that caused from earthquake and Buddha statue thieves

Tips: Open Tue-Sun from 06.30-16.30. It’s recommended to book a ticket in advance. Temple ground ticket Child 240k IDR / Adult 400k IDR – available all day. Temple structure Child 305k IDR / Adult 455k IDR – schedule start at 08.30

*Ticket included tour guide, canvas bag, a pair of flip-flops that required to wear when visited the temple structure

name: ajleeblog
text:
Prambanan, located on the island of Java in Indonesia, stands as a striking testament to the region's rich cultural and religious heritage. This UNESCO World Heritage site is a marvel of Hindu architecture, rivaling the grandeur of any ancient temple complex globally.

The towering spires of Prambanan, dedicated to the Trimurti—Brahma, Vishnu, and Shiva—create an imposing skyline that beckons visitors to explore its intricacies. The main temple, devoted to Shiva, is an architectural masterpiece with its soaring height and detailed reliefs depicting scenes from Hindu epics, such as the Ramayana.

Wandering through Prambanan's expansive grounds is like navigating a sacred labyrinth. The smaller temples dedicated to Vishnu and Brahma, adorned with delicate carvings and statues, contribute to the site's overall majesty. As the sun sets, the temple complex is bathed in a warm, ethereal glow, creating a mystical ambiance that enhances the spiritual experience.

Prambanan's restoration efforts have preserved its historical significance, allowing visitors to marvel at the craftsmanship of the past. The intricately carved bas-reliefs narrate tales of divine battles and celestial beings, providing a visual feast for those seeking to unravel the layers of Javanese mythology.

Beyond its historical and architectural splendor, Prambanan serves as a vibrant cultural hub. Periodic dance performances, especially the Ramayana Ballet, bring the ancient narratives to life, creating a sensory journey that combines sight, sound, and tradition.

In conclusion, Prambanan is a treasure trove of art, history, and spirituality. Its resplendent temples and cultural vibrancy make it an indispensable destination for those eager to immerse themselves in Indonesia's profound and captivating past.
title: Prambanan Temple

name: Vic M
text:
Temple’s are amazing to see but animal cruelty on site is completely unacceptable.

After doing a circuit of the complex we came across an area with deer, cassowaries and peacocks which was really upsetting to see. Definitely concerns around animal welfare here with what looked like injured deer in dirty conditions, birds in tiny cages and all had little to no shade. People come here to see the UNESCO site, this treatment of animals is completely unnecessary, besides the point that there is actually plenty of space on site to give these animals a decent standard of living if it is insisted they remain there.

Regarding the temples themselves, yes it is more expensive for foreigners to enter but be reminded that this is a UNESCO site and consider what you would pay if this was anywhere else in the world.

There are 4 sites on this complex, the first is the biggest and main attraction for most, and whilst it is impressive we actually preferred the last as no-one else seems to bother going there so we pretty much had the site to ourselves. It is the least restored of the 4 but this didn’t bother us as it is a reminder of the history and also how impressive the restorations actually are.

Overall we enjoyed our visit but the situation with the animals needs to change and also be aware that if there are groups of school children around the main site, as a foreigner you will likely be approached so they can ask you questions whilst being filmed for their school project.

We got the local bus here rather than paying for tour etc which was easy enough with the direction of our homestay and much cheaper.

text:
I've visited Prambanan more than ten times since I was a child, and I would gladly go again if I had the chance because I love the atmosphere. Some parts of the temple offer shady areas with pleasant walking trails. When I visited last year with my colleague, it was especially nice to stroll along these paths.

Back when I was in college, I camped at their campground, located in the west-wing area. It’s a good spot for groups, with space for around 30–50 people and basic facilities like electricity outlets and toilets.

This year, I returned for the Mandiri Jogja Marathon event and discovered that the park area can be rented for events—something I hadn’t known before.

For first-time visitors, I highly recommend going in the morning. Be sure to purchase the combined ticket with Ratu Boko Temple to save yourself the hassle of traveling there separately. The ticket includes a free shuttle service to Ratu Boko, making the experience even more convenient.

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia
name: rkwphoon
text: Borobudur, the crown jewel of Yogjakarta. We heard from our tour guide that Borobudur had been closed for the last three years and had just opened to the public about a month ago. And along with its opening, they are trialing a new system of limiting the number of attendees, how they access the park, and new entrance fees in order to preserve the park and the temple. First things first, the entrance fees. To access the top of the temple, for me, a foreigner, it costs 455,000 IDR. For local it costs 120,000 IDR. I am used to paying more to get into various attractions in Indonesia however, this difference is stark and unfair in my opinion. Hopefully, once their trial is over they will adjust the price to where it's more reasonable. After getting the ticket, we were then given these sandals to wear in the park and they are mandatory. You get to keep the sandals after your tour. One of my friends had expressed that the sandals were quite uncomfortable to walk on but I didn't have issues with them. After that we were split up into groups, each group assigned to an Indonesian-speaking or an English-speaking guide who would then guide us around in the park. We were forewarned by our guide before starting our tour that we were forbidden from straying from the group that we were in. Doing so would cause us to be removed from the park without further reasoning. Our guide gave us our tour of and a lot of history to do with the temple. Very interesting stuff. And of course, we got quite a few photo-ops while on the tour. I recommend wearing a hat and bringing extra water for this tour. It gets quite hot there. This of course is a must-do activity while in Yogjakarta. As with any large attractions in Indonesia, be wary of the souvenir vendors. A lot of them were quite aggressive.

The event was heavily attended by around tens of thousands of visitors with various Buddhist ceremonies, reading prayers, group meditation, and so on. If you want to visit this temple, make sure to book your hotel well in advance, because the hotels around are full on the day of the event.

title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: TORY
text:
I came to jogja to feel indonesian traditional culture enough.

I learned gamulan music in jogja before I visit here, and when I got here, always can hear adorable gamulan music from the speaker.

The temple was pretty huge, and very beautiful on camera, but in fact too busy with too many visitors, cannot think and feel the temple's heritage or messeges due to the many of visitors.

Everywhere was noisy with group visitors, hard to get photo without them

The sun light was really direct on us, but not enough place to hide of it,

The area where the statue was located inside the tower was so dark that you couldn't see an inch in front of you, and it was full of a disgusting smell, so I had to move quickly to get there.

There were many pieces that were still being restored, and it was unfortunate that it felt like they were being neglected rather than being managed with care overall.

After looking around the temple for about an hour, I was so exhausted from the direct sunlight, too high and narrow stairs, and the disgusting smell that I returned to my accommodation without looking around any further.
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Kristina
text:
I LOVE the Prambanan temple. I personally think it’s better than the Borobudur temple by a long shot. The temples are stunning and you can enter them! How lovely.

The grounds are quite massive and they have a shuttle bus to transport between some sites, but the schedule isn’t clear nor reliable. There is a museum, but there are no English translations available. I do feel the $60 USD entry fee could’ve been better delegated to address these things.

However, it’s still worth every penny!
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Alla Goncharova
text:
It is a very popular temple, and if you are a foreigner, you will be as much an exhibit to the locals as the temple itself. Get ready for requests for a picture together.
We were lucky enough to be there when the local school kids were brought in for a tour and we took pictures with two classes with all of them together and each one individually ) it was fun.

The temple complex itself is open to the public almost all the way through. Don't forget to take water, there will be nowhere to buy it on the grounds, you can buy it in the stores around the perimeter of the park.
There is an opportunity to rent an electric scooter. Minimum time is 15 minutes. It is convenient to get to other temple buildings, such as Sewu.
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Rahmat BPP JKT
text:
I came back to this place after almost 1 decade! The 50k entry ticket is not too expensive compared to the extra care to preserve the preservation of this historic place even though I entered at a ticket price of 25k (students understand). The older this place the more beautiful. Prambanan is very well maintained, and extraordinary care.

Since 2010, when you enter Prambanan Temple, you have to wear a batik sarong because it was indirectly a place of worship for Hindus in ancient times. Foreign tourists usually wear shorts. As a result, to respect Prambanan Temple as a place of worship, he was given a batik sarong
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Darren Grubb
text:
This is an amazing 8th / 9th century Hindi   collection of temples that must be visited.  Prambanan Temple is just a part of the wider Hindi / Buddhist complex.  The stone reliefs depict the Hindu pantheon, legends, and interestingly birds that are not native to the area, demonstrating broad trade networks during that time.

It can be visited in an hour, but to appreciate the site, half a day is needed.

But more amazing than the temple was the hospitality of the locals...especially the school kids...who found any excuse to take a picture with a foreigner and make our visit as enjoyable as it could be
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: DANI MUBAROK
text: Prambanan Temple in Yogyakarta is an impressive manifestation of architectural wonder and cultural heritage. The intricacies and precision in the construction of these temples provide a captivating experience for every visitor. The grand and historically rich architecture creates a mystical and awe-inspiring atmosphere. Through beautiful and monumental relief decorations, Prambanan Temple not only stands as a valuable Hindu-Buddhist historical relic but also offers unparalleled views. A visit to Prambanan Temple is a journey through time, combining the beauty of art, history, and spirituality into an extraordinary unity.
title: Prambanan Temple

The descriptions aren't always accurate - not to take away from the Prambanan status but it's simply not the biggest Hindu temple site in SEA as it says on one of the tables (Angkor Wat) bitvtze biggest in Indonesia.

title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Pete Silva
text:
Nice indu temple in Yogyakarta.
As a foreigner you'll pay around Rp 350/375k compare with the, below 100k for the locals.
This temple has a lot of ruins from an earthquake.
You'll be able to go inside the chambers where you can find statues of each Indu God.
You're allowed to take pictures.
Be aware that there will be around one hour that you'll not be able to get inside the main chamber which is during the prayers.

The park has other attractions such as games for kids, traditional toys, golf cart, bicycles.

For the waiting people there are massage chairs that you can rent.

Umbrellas can be rented at the entry as the sun can be very hot some days.

A lot, but I mean, A LOT of gift shops where you can buy souvenirs.

You have dears and peacocks 🦚  also.

There is a lot of photographers who can take your picture and print them out before you leave. It's around Rp10 to 20k.

Bring comfortable shoes.
title: Prambanan Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Sua Truong
text:
Warning: if you go ahead of your group past the fenced area to the steps of the temple, you will NOT be permitted back to the park area before the steps.
This poorly understood logic and no warning signs (at least not in English) to give visitors warning was a bad experience to start.
There's local price and foreigner pricing... Yeah. I understand but not acceptable anywhere else except in developing countries.
The temples themselves were quite impressive and immense. Perhaps not staggering as Incan temples or Egyptian pyramids but still magnificent to look at.
If you come really early, then you're probably going to get great photos but if you don't then use the trees and hedges to block areas to take better photos.
If you go to the right side towards the exit, there's a great area to take photos without anyone seen in the background.
The forced exit makes you go through the market area where hordes of vendors sell nearly identical stuff as each other. If you're really into these, the sellers in the middle and near the back (end area) will offer better pricing or more open to negotiations.
Garden area is great for rest and small zoo area is okay but the cages looks small for the trapped animals. Sort of feel sorry for them.

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia
name: Dan
text:
One star for the temple grounds ticket. Such a waste of money, effort and time.

The grounds should be free.

There's nothing to do or see as the temple has a terrible perspective whilst looking from ground level. They sell the ticket at about 90% of the temple structure ticket which sells out months prior to local scalpers. Who can purchase the ticket for next to 25k rupiah then sell online for 1 million to tourists.
The mark up from local to tourist is astronomical.

If you think that the temple itself may be of interest think again.
There isn't even access to get close enough to view any carvings or statues. You basically can walk a perimeter then leave.

The perimeter you can walk around has zero carvings and is brand new, takes about 10 minutes. You keep thinking it's going to get better but it doesn't.

Don't think like me that they would at least let you on the first level. They have barricades around the whole place and you need a wrist band and special shoes to even step near the temple.

All you see is the brand new bricks they laid recently. You can't even view any bells or the top.

All the statues at the mid to higher levels have been decapitated and not replaced.

You're basically paying 90% of a full ticket price to watch from outside the temple. In the blistering sun with no shade or cover.

Pic below is about as close as you can get.

name: Bella Carina Putri
text:
If you want to visit the biggest  ancient Buddhist Temple in Indonesia, this is the place 😀

It's comfortable to visit with quite good management. There are 2 options of tickets, whether you just want to visit the area surrounding or you want to climb up the temple. But you have to set the scheduled time if you want to visit the temple and I recommend you to buy the tickets at least 1 day before your visit (please check the forecast before you do it).

They will guide you on how you go up the temple. We choose to go up to the temple. And you will need to change your shoes to the provided sandals (upanat). Then you'll be in a group with a guide with your preference language there (Indonesia or English), based on the tickets that you choose in the beginning (2 options of story explanation). If you're a local who wants a tour in English, you can still buy a local ticket online with an added charge of IDR 10K by informing the ticketing booth on site before you go in.

address: Jl. Badrawati, Kw. Candi Borobudur, Borobudur, Kec. Borobudur, Kabupaten Magelang, Jawa Tengah, Indonesia
name: Cameron Keyser
text: Worth the money coming to explore this beautiful temple. We came in the middle of the day and started the climb up the temple around 2 which was very hot, I would recommend coming earlier or later to avoid the heat. The temple itself was amazing and had a lot of history behind it. The number of people heading to the top of the temple is limited, so make sure to plan ahead, as you will need to be accompanied by a guide. You get a free water and pair of slippers that you can keep as a souvenir for when you ascend the temple so it does not get damaged. The guided tour is around an hour and a half with 30 mins explanation about the history of the temple before starting the ascent. Then you have an hour once you get your ticket scanned and start the climb. Our guide did a great job explaining the carvings and different levels of the temple and then we were given 20 minutes to explore the upper tier and to take photos on our own. Luckily since they limit the number of tourists, it wasn’t so crowded at the top and you can get a great picture. I definitely recommend the ticket where you climb to the top, otherwise the experience may not be as worth it. This place is a must see when in Yogyakarta
title: Borobudur Temple

address: Jl. Raya Solo - Yogyakarta No.16, Kranggan, Bokoharjo, Kec. Prambanan, Kabupaten Sleman, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55571, Indonesia
name: Cameron Keyser
text:
Would like to give this temple complex a higher rating but it was simply too expensive and was kind of disappointing that they charge tourists 7.5x the price the locals pay (we paid 750000 IDR for 2 adults). I feel like with that price maybe a water, umbrella (to stay out of the sun) or parking should be included.

The Prambanan temple itself was pretty impressive… can’t imagine how it would have looked when all of the smaller surrounding structures were still standing. We were lucky to have some students who were practicing their English approach us and give us a free tour. It was nice to learn a bit about the area without having to pay an extra 150000 IDR for a guide.

The entrance ticket also included Lumbung, Bubrah and Sewu temples.The Sewu temple was by far the best out of those but it was about 750m walk from the Prambanan temple. You can pay 15k-30k to rent a bike or electric scooter for 20-30 mins to make it down there but we elected to walk… it was really hot 😂.

The also have some animals to check out like deer, peacocks and cassowaries. However it was a bit sad to see these animals in such small cages and exposed to the sun.

Overall, it was pretty cool but once again, giving this rating due to the price of the ticket and the poor animals.

text:
Candi Prambanan
The Prambanan Hindu temple

The second largest Hindu temple complex ever built outside India was the Prambanan temple in central Java, Indonesia. Second only to the majestic Angkor in Cambodia, this huge complex dedicated to the Trimurty (Trinity) of the hindu Pantheon was completed in 850 CE and there were 240 temples in the complex. Due to the volcanic activity of Mount Merapi, it was abandoned in the 10th century CE and fell into ruins. Today only a few remain standing.

Prambanan is some 16 Km NE of Yogyakarta. When I went to Yogyakarta (Jogja) I had three places in mind. Borobudur, Mount Merapi, and Prambanan. I did the two except Merapi which I couldn't. The Indonesian government has been taking up the restoration work from time to time. The last devastation that occurred to the temple was on 27 May 2006 when an earthquake struck the area.

One magnificent temple complex every visitor to Indonesia ought to make a point to visit.

text:
Prambanan, named after the village, is the biggest temple complex in Java. There are 224 temples in the complex; three of them, the main temples are Brahma Temple in the north, Vishnu Temple in the south, and the biggest among the three which lies between Brahma and Vishnu temples is Shiva Temple (47 meters high).

These three ancient masterpieces of Hindu architecture are locally referred to as Prambanan Temple or Lorojonggrang Temple. One of its appeals is the wealth of sculptural detail. The well known one is on the inner wall of the balustrade, the wonderfully vital and utterly engrossing Ramayana epic.

Perhaps one of the most majestic temples in the South-East Asia, Prambanan attracts many admirers each year from abroad. Situated about 15 kilometers from Yogyakarta, the top of the main shrine is visible from a great distance and rises high above the scattered ruins of the former temples.

Prambanan is the best seen shortly after dawn or in the late afternoon. However it is still beautiful at any time.
Enjoy sunrise behind the glory of Prambanan Temple. Visitors should be at the location - in the area of The Open Air Theater and archaeological park of the temple - before sun rise at about 5:00 o'clock in the morning.

text:
Visiting the largest Buddhist temple in the world and one of the most interesting UNESCO World sites, and one of the seven Wonders of the world was one of the highlights of my trip. Navigating around when and how to go, which kind of ticket to buy, was challenging. I heard a lot of stories and with this review I am hoping to provide an accurate up to date experience

Q: Are the sunrise tours canceled?
A: Yes they are, unless you are staying in the Manohara hotel, they have a special private Tour

Q: When should I go?
A: The 1st tour starts at 8:30am, if you will buy tickets on site, make sure to be there at least 1 hour before, so 7 to 7:30. They only allow 1200 visitors per day on the temple itself, so don't arrive later than, noon, because not only it will be so crowded and you might miss entry, the scorching sun will burn you, especially on the temple, being it made from black volcanic stone

Q: Can I get on top of the temple?
A: Providing that you buy an extension of the temple ground ticket, you can, only with a guide with a max time limit of 1 hr. The temple has 7 levels, the max reachable level is 6. The last level is off limits to public, only reserved for high religious figures

Q: Should I buy tickets on site or online? What kind of tickets is available?
A: I prefer to buy tickets on site since there are so many outlets selling them, which might end up being fake tickets. There are two types of tickets, temple ground and temple structure. With the ground one you will only be allowed access around the temple but not on top of it, so you should buy the temple structure ticket, which will cost you 455,000IDR or 30 dollars, which personally I found very expensive, however since this place is one of a kind it's totally worth it

Q: Is the tour organized? Can I roam on my own?
A: Yes a few tours leave every 30 mins starting 8:30am, each tour is assigned a number. You will have to follow your tour guide and group at all times, which is part of the ticket. They will give you a slipper to wear, because you are not allowed with normal shoes on the temple structure. Your guide will explain the history of the temple and everything you nerd to know. There is mineral water provided. There will be 15 mins free time to roam and take pictures in the end on the structure. On the temple ground itself you can stay as much as you want

I believe a better job can be done in organizing the tours, streamlining all the information about the visit online to make it easier for tourists to access and enjoy their experience to the maximum

text:
Borobudur Temple
Borobudur Temple is a magnificent and iconic Buddhist temple located in Central Java, Indonesia. It is one of the most famous and important historical sites in the country and is recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Here's a review of Borobudur Temple: Historical and Cultural Significance: Borobudur Temple holds immense historical and cultural value. Built in the 9th century during the Sailendra Dynasty, the temple is a masterpiece of Indonesian architecture and art. It showcases the blending of Buddhist influences with indigenous Javanese architecture and serves as a symbol of Indonesia's ancient past. Architectural Marvel: The temple's design is awe-inspiring and unique. It is constructed as a massive stone mandala, with a pyramid-like structure consisting of nine stacked platforms. The lower levels have intricate reliefs depicting Buddhist teachings and stories, while the upper levels house stupas, each containing a statue of the Buddha. Spiritual Experience: Visitors often describe Borobudur Temple as a serene and spiritual place. The ambiance is tranquil, especially during early morning or late afternoon visits. Climbing to the top of the temple offers panoramic views of the surrounding lush landscapes and nearby volcanic mountains. Sunrise and Sunset Views: The temple is famous for its breathtaking sunrise and sunset views. Many tourists and locals flock to the site to witness the sun rising or setting behind the temple's stupas, creating a magical and unforgettable experience. Crowds and Weather: Borobudur Temple is a popular tourist destination, so it can get quite crowded, especially during peak seasons. To avoid the crowds, visiting early in the morning or later in the afternoon is recommended. Weather in the region can be hot and humid, so it's advisable to bring appropriate clothing and stay hydrated. Preservation Efforts: Over the years, the temple has undergone significant restoration and preservation efforts to protect it from natural disasters and decay. These efforts have been vital in maintaining the temple's structural integrity and ensuring it remains accessible to visitors for generations to come. Overall, Borobudur Temple is a must-visit destination for history enthusiasts, culture lovers, and anyone seeking a spiritual connection. It offers a fascinating glimpse into Indonesia's rich heritage and is a remarkable testament to the artistry and ingenuity of ancient civilizations.
title: Borobudur Temple

text:
Being one of the best heritage sites in the  world, this temple represents the whole identity of Indonesia and it is a must-see when you are in Indonesia. There are postive and negative feedbacks that I would like to share.

(+) Positives:
- The management in this temple has been positively changed drastically comparing 5-10 years ago.
- The price (50k Rupiah) is reasonable  for domestic and with that price it includes a sandal, a bag and a guide accompany with you. The guides can speak many languages such as English, Dutch, Bahasa Indonesia and probably others . So for those who have some trouble understanding English this is a  great option.
- They limit the number of people so that the temple would not be too full and could cause some damage to the foundation of it. Also with less people its easy to take photos 📷🤳

(-) Negatives:
-I reccomend you to not come between 11:00-15:00 especially during holidays because its super hot and too crowded . I highly recommend you to come early in the morning between 6-10.
- After you enter you will see some photographer wanting you to get a photo from them. DO NOT ACCEPT THEM because they can charge you HUGELY.  Let your guides take a photo for you.
- 250k Rupiah for a foreigner price is a little bit overprice imo. You still get the same accomodation as the domestic gets but it is a bit unfair for a 30-60 minute visit of the temple. I think 150k is the best price for foreigners.

Additional advice: Its good to book the tickets early through their official website so that you don't have to wait the long queue.
